# AGENTS-user.md is the user-facing guide for running the derived
# sandbox.  Fill in the sections below with details specific to your
# application.

# User guide

Overview paragraph: what this sandbox wraps and what it is for.  Link
to the upstream application's documentation.

## Prerequisites

- Docker and Docker Compose
- Linux kernel 5.6+ (for built-in WireGuard support)
- <add application-specific requirements — GPU drivers, host services, etc.>

## Quick start

```sh
cp router/config.example.toml router/config.toml
cp compose.override.example.yml compose.override.yml
# edit both files as needed
docker compose -f compose.yml -f compose.override.yml build
docker compose -f compose.yml -f compose.override.yml up
```

## Configuration

### `router/config.toml`

List the `[services.<name>]` blocks this application actually needs and
briefly explain why.

### `compose.override.yml`

List the `SUISOU__<ENV>` markers this application uses and which service
each one authenticates against.  Reference `AGENTS-suisou.md` for the
marker convention.

### Secrets

Recommend a secrets manager (Doppler / 1Password CLI / `op run`).
Inline command-line secrets are recorded in shell history and in any
AI-agent session context, so avoid them.

## Exposed ports

List the ports this application publishes on `wg-client` and how users
connect (directly, via SSH tunnel, etc.).

## External service integrations

For each third-party service the application talks to (LLM provider,
storage, etc.), cover:

1. How to register / obtain credentials.
2. Which `SUISOU__<ENV>` marker corresponds to which secret.
3. Which `[services.<name>]` block in `config.toml` allows traffic to
   that service.

## Updating the core from the template

When `suisou-template` publishes a security fix, pull it in with the
`git checkout template/main -- <paths>` recipe documented in
`AGENTS-suisou.md`.
